# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eckley-brinton-coxe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The **American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical, and Petroleum Engineers** (**AIME**) is a professional association for mining and metallurgy, with over 145,000 members.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The association was founded in 1871 by 22 mining engineers in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania, and was one of the first national engineering societies in the country.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] It is the parent organization of four Member Societies, the Society for Mining, Metallurgy, and Exploration (SME), The Minerals, Metals & Materials Society (TMS), the Association for Iron and Steel Technology (AIST), and the Society of Petroleum Engineers (SPE).
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The organization is currently based in San Ramon, California.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] Founded as the **American Institute of Mining Engineers** (AIME), the institute had a membership at the beginning of 1915 of over 5,000, made up of honorary, elected, and associate members.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The annual meeting of the institute was held in February, with other meetings during the year as authorized by the council.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The institute published three volumes of *Transactions* annually and a monthly *Bulletin* which appeared on the first of each month.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The headquarters of the institute was in the Engineering Societies' Building in New York City.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] Following creation of the Petroleum Division in 1922, the Iron and Steel Division in 1928 and the Institute of Metals Division in 1933 the name of the society was changed in 1957 to the American Institute of Mining, Metallurgical and Petroleum Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] Three of the current member societies were then created from the divisions, increasing to four in 1974 when the Iron and Steel Society (ISS) was formed.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] In 2004 ISS merged with the Association of Iron and Steel Engineers (AISE) to form the Association for Iron and Steel Technology (AIST) whilst remaining a member society of AIME.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The society presents around 25 awards each year at its annual conference.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] Member societies also disburse their own awards, including the Percy Nicholls Award, awarded by SME jointly with American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The following individuals have held the position of President of this organization.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-institute-of-mining-engineers] The Society for Mining, Metallurgy & Exploration publishes the monthly magazine *Mining Engineering* since 1949.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe was instrumental in the formation of Lehigh University in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, which began as a mining school in 1865, and founded the Institute of Miners and Mechanics in 1879.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He served as president of the American Institute of Mining Engineers from 1878 to 1880 and of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers from 1893 to 1894.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He was granted more than 100 patents related to mining and industrial technology.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He served as a Democratic member of the Pennsylvania State Senate for the 21st district from 1881 to 1884.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe was born June 4, 1839, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, to Charles Sidney Coxe and Anna Maria Brinton.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] His great-great-grandfather was Daniel Coxe, his grandfather was Tench Coxe, a prominent political economist and landowner, and his cousin was George B.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Through inheritance and family ownership, the Coxe family retained extensive coal-bearing lands in northeastern Pennsylvania that later formed the basis of the Coxe coal enterprises.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe graduated from the University of Pennsylvania in 1858 with degrees in Chemistry and Physics.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He spent six months after graduation in the Lehigh Valley region of Pennsylvania conducting a topographical geology survey of his grandfather's 35,000-acre estate under the supervision of Benjamin Smith Lyman.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The survey documented portions of the coal-bearing lands that would later become central to the family's mining operations.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] In 1860, he traveled to Europe and studied for two years at the École des Mines in Paris, France, and for one year at the Freiberg Mining Academy in Freiberg, Saxony.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He spent an additional two years studying mines in England and continental Europe and returned to the United States in 1864.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] His extensive European mining education provided technical expertise that would later be applied to the development and management of the family's anthracite coal interests.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Eckley's grandfather, Tench Coxe, had purchased 800,000 acres of land in Pennsylvania and urged his heirs to hold on to the land as he suspected coal would be found in the region.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Tench's son, Charles, was able to retain ownership of 35,000 acres and left it to his sons including Eckley.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coal was found in the Coxe owned land and the Coxe Brothers and Company mining company was founded in 1865 with the first mine opened in Drifton, Pennsylvania.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] By the late 1800s, the company was the largest independent producer of anthracite coal with nearly 4,000 employees, coal shipments in excess of 1.5 million tons and land assets valued at $10 million.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The Coxe Brothers & Company organization became the Cross Creek Coal Company led by Coxe, and in 1890 Coxe organized and became president of the Delaware, Susquehanna and Schuylkill Railroad.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He lectured frequently before scientific bodies.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He published several technical papers on mining and translated the first volume of Julius Weisbach's "Mechanics of Engineering and Construction of Machines" from German to English in 1872.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He was instrumental in the founding of Lehigh University in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania as a mining school in 1865 and served on its board of trustees until his death.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] In 1877, his mines were selected by the Columbia College School of Mines for their study program due to the quality of the mines.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He founded the Institute for Miners and Mechanics in 1879 in Freeland, Pennsylvania.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The intent of the school was to teach math, science and English to the men working in the mines.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe was a staunch opponent of organized labor and played a leading role in defeating two major unions during one of the longest strikes in the anthracite coal industry, from September 1887 to March 1888.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The defeat of the strike weakened miners' ability to collectively bargain for higher wages, safer working conditions, and greater protections against the power of coal operators.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Labor historians have cited the conflict as an example of the immense economic and political influence exercised by coal companies during the late nineteenth century, when workers and their families often faced significant hardship during labor disputes.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Critics argue that Coxe's resistance to unionization helped preserve a system in which mine owners retained overwhelming control over employment, housing, and the daily lives of mining families throughout the region.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He was a member of the American Society of Civil Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He was elected as a member in 1870 to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] In 1880 Coxe was one of the original founders of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He served as the president of the American Institute of Mining Engineers from May 1878 to February 1880 and as vice president of the Institute of Mechanical Engineers from April 1880 to November 1881.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Critics of the anthracite coal industry have pointed to the Coxe enterprises as an example of the enormous economic influence wielded by coal operators during the Gilded Age and Progressive Era.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The wealth accumulated through these enterprises stood in stark contrast to the conditions experienced by many miners and their families, whose labor generated the profits that fueled the expansion of the coal empire.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe was an inventor who was granted over 100 patents.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He developed a long steel tape for the measurement of land by surveyors and the traveling grate, which he patented in 1893.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He served as chairman of the Pennsylvania delegation to the Democratic National Convention in Chicago in 1884.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Records in the Coxe Brothers collection indicate that after being elected in 1880, Coxe initially declined to take the oath of office because he stated he could not swear that all campaign funds had been spent in compliance with the requirements of Pennsylvania law at the time.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He later addressed this publicly to his constituents.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] He died May 13, 1895, of pneumonia and was interred at Saint James Episcopal Churchyard in Drifton, Pennsylvania.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Eckley Miners' Village in Pennsylvania was named for him in 1857 by his father.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] The Coxe Hall (1910) at Lehigh University, originally a mining laboratory, is named after him.
[src:eckley-brinton-coxe/eckley-brinton-coxe] Coxe was admitted to the National Inventors Hall of Fame in 2006 for his work on the traveling-grate furnace.
